==Old English==
===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /'fædeɹ/
===Etymology===
Common Germanic *''[[fader]]'' from Indo-European ''*ph₂ter-''.

Germanic cognates: Old Frisian ''feder'', Old Saxon ''fadar'' (Dutch ''[[vader]]''), Old High German ''[[fater]]'' (German ''[[Vater]]''), Old Franconian ''fader'', Old Norse ''[[faðir]]'' (Swedish ''[[fader]]''), Gothic [[𐍆𐌰𐌳𐌰𐍂]].

Indo-European cognates: Greek ''[[πατήρ]]'', Latin ''[[pater]]'', Armenian [[հայր]], Old Irish ''athir'' (Irish ''[[athair]]'')
===Noun===
'''fæder''' ''m''

# a [[father]]
#:''Ðis is se ilca God, ðone fæderas cuðon'': this is the same god, whom your fathers knew.  (''Legend of St Andrew'')

